Anonymous Sun 07 Mar 2021 07:42:18 No.36881303 Report
Quoted By:
>>36880441
Part is pantsing the fuck out of things, and part is figuring out the structure as you go.
I'll use my current (and completely unread here because it's in the first draft stage) project as an example.
The title and character name came first, then the opening paragraphs. So I had the vibe/setting/character penciled in. Second character walks on. By the end of that scene I have a plot thread (figuring out why Character B needed to hire Character A), a couple conflicts (between other mentioned characters and situations) and motivations.
After that it's let the setting fill in a few blanks. As it fleshes out things, I write a rough outline and synopsis. The connections build up. Write, revisit, repeat until done.
Do I know the end? Yes, the last scene is clear. The few before then are starting to take shape; the last cards are down for conflicts and motivations. Think of it this way: Star Wars - Luke found the burnt corpse of his aunt & uncle. That made him a different man than Han Solo prior to the Death Star attack.
Sometimes you scrap a scene. It's not useful enough. Same for characters. But my rule of thumb is I don't know anything until that first draft is done. The pieces click. I've heard of artists turning a piece upside down or to one side to find flaws. In writing you might trace another character for a bit to work out who is lying.

But the biggest help is that every action has a consequence. Innocent ones snowball into the endgame. You reward the reader for finishing a scene, but give bonus treats for recalling things with you. Engage them. Let them guess. Sometimes you tell them they were right, others you show why the guess wasn't good.
There is no clear set of progress guidelines like with art. You can only hope the jumble in your head wraps up, that no one pulls an about face that makes way more sense than whatever you thought up a week ago, and that you don't write plot holes worse than a novice artist draws hands.

>>36892781
Its inspired by it.
The self revelation is the best part, the action part where the character changes.
The weakness is how the character is from the start and what they're changinf from. Your mc has a good weakness if the mc is hurting someone else with it. The need is not the self revelation but what they have to do to not have the weakness. Think of it like a generalization that they're doing the opposite of until the self revelation.
The desire is what the character wants. Be specific.
The opponent wants the same thing as the character. They have different views than the mc . Make sure their are four. In a romance, the opponent is the love interest. The mcs weakness causes them to not get together.
The plan is what the mc is going to do to to beat the opponent and achieve the desire.
The battle is the height of the story, right before the self revelation. It is a traumatic experience, the culmination of the plan being executed by the mc against the opponent.
The self revelation occurs after the battle and is the result of it. But you come up with the self revelation first.
The new equilibrium Is life after your mc has changed. In a romance, he gets the waifur.
